I reproduced the failure: `tests/bitwise.be` exits with an assertion failure at line 13, `assert(~a == -12)`. The literal version on line 14 is not reached during the test, but a separate probe showed `~11` prints `-12` while `a = 11; ~a` prints `-11`. That proves parsing and constant folding for integer bit-flip are correct, while runtime execution of the `OP_FLIP` bytecode is wrong. Inspecting the VM dispatch confirms this: the `OP_FLIP` case uses unary arithmetic negation (`-a->v.i`) instead of bitwise complement (`~a->v.i`).

ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_vm.c:746` in the `opcase(FLIP)` runtime bytecode handler computes `var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);`. This is the implementation for unary minus, not bitwise flip. Constant expressions such as `~11` are handled earlier by `src/be_code.c:609` using `~e->v.i`, so only non-literal/runtime values like `~a` are affected. For `a == 11`, runtime returns `-11` instead of the two's-complement bitwise complement `-12`, causing `assert(~a == -12)` to fail.

LOCAL FIX: Replace arithmetic negation with bitwise complement in the `OP_FLIP` integer branch:
```diff
diff --git a/src/be_vm.c b/src/be_vm.c
--- a/src/be_vm.c
+++ b/src/be_vm.c
@@ -743,7 +743,7 @@
         opcase(FLIP): {
             bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();
             if (var_isint(a)) {
-                var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);
+                var_setint(dst, ~a->v.i);
             } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {
                 ins_unop(vm, "~", *RKB());
                 reg = vm->reg;
```

GLOBAL FIX: Centralize unary integer operator semantics so compile-time constant folding and runtime bytecode dispatch cannot diverge. For example, introduce helper functions/macros such as `be_int_neg(bint x)` and `be_int_flip(bint x)`, use them both in `src/be_code.c` constant folding and in `src/be_vm.c` opcode execution, and add VM-level regression tests that compare folded and non-folded forms for every unary/binary operator (`~11` vs `a=11; ~a`, `-11` vs `a=11; -a`, etc.). This prevents copy/paste opcode-handler mistakes from producing different semantics for literals and variables.
